The selectivity, anti-interference ability, and the potential in real sample detection of this N-CDs@Zr based sensor were tested (Fig. 5
                         and Table 1
                        ). Common interfering substances included various ions, amino acids, antibiotics, and small molecules. Selectivity and anti-interference experiments were conducted by adding different substances, such as Ca2+, Mg2+, Na+, glutamate, tryptophan, arginine, amoxicillin, and others (Fig. 5). The results suggested good selectivity and its robust anti-interference performance for OTCs. While, we need to point out that certain analogues of OTC can cause interference with detection (Fig. S16). This issue can potentially be addressed in future studies, and we are exploring solutions to further enhance the selectivity. The standard addition method (Table 1).
